qas.question: Where did the Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg move his residence to?
Who elevated the status of the Dukes of Brunswick-Lüneburg?
Who confirmed the elevation of the Dukes of Brunswick-Lüneburg in 1708?
Which other nation would the electors of Hanover become monarchs of?
Who was the first elector from Hanover to sit on the British throne?
What Duke moved to Hanover in 1736?
Who elevated the Duke of Brunswick to the rank of Prince?
Who was the last Elector of Hanover to sit on the British throne?
Who abdicated the British throne in 1714?
What other title did three queens of Great Britain with United kingdom also hold?

context: In 1636 <b5_0>George, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg<b5_0/>, ruler of the Brunswick-Lüneburg principality of Calenberg, moved his residence to <a0_0>Hanover<a0_0/>. The Dukes of Brunswick-Lüneburg were elevated by <b6_0>the <a1_0>Holy Roman Emperor<b6_0/><a1_0/> to the rank of Prince-Elector in 1692, and this elevation was confirmed by the <a2_0>Imperial Diet<a2_0/> in 1708. Thus the principality was upgraded to the Electorate of Brunswick-Lüneburg, colloquially known as the Electorate of Hanover after Calenberg's capital (see also: House of Hanover). Its electors would later become monarchs of <a3_0>Great Britain<a3_0/> (and from 1801, of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland). The first of these was <a4_0><b7_0><b8_0>George I Louis<b7_0/><a4_0/>,<b8_0/> who acceded to the British throne in 1714. The last British monarch who ruled in Hanover was William IV. Semi-Salic law, which required succession by the male line if possible, forbade the accession of Queen Victoria in Hanover. As a male-line descendant of George I, Queen Victoria was herself a member of the House of Hanover. Her descendants, however, bore her husband's titular name of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. Three kings of Great Britain, or the United Kingdom, were concurrently also <b9_0>Electoral Princes of Hanover<b9_0/>.
